00:42:01,418 --> 00:42:03,386
- Oh, we've got a problem.
- What is it?

510
00:42:03,420 --> 00:42:04,910
Damn slugs, look at this.

511
00:42:04,955 --> 00:42:07,219
- Look look.
- Oh.

512
00:42:07,258 --> 00:42:09,226
If there's one
there's probably more, right?

513
00:42:09,260 --> 00:42:11,057
Yeah, it looks like it, ma'am.

514
00:42:13,497 --> 00:42:15,192
You're not gonna eat my babies.

515
00:42:15,232 --> 00:42:18,565
Miss, you can-- apples.
My mother swore by apples.

516
00:42:18,602 --> 00:42:19,864
Apples?

517
00:42:19,904 --> 00:42:21,735
Yeah, we grew spinach
and potatoes in our yard.

518
00:42:21,772 --> 00:42:24,366
We couldn't afford to lose them--
it was mostly all that we had to eat,

519
00:42:24,408 --> 00:42:26,239
so my mother would put
down slices of apple

520
00:42:26,277 --> 00:42:28,336
to attract the slugs and
the caterpillars elsewhere

521
00:42:28,379 --> 00:42:30,347
and lead them away
from the vegetables.

522
00:42:30,381 --> 00:42:32,372
- And that worked?
- It did, yeah.

523
00:42:36,520 --> 00:42:39,284
If this works, I'm sending
your mother a check.

524
00:42:39,323 --> 00:42:41,086
Well, that's very generous
of you, ma'am,

525
00:42:41,125 --> 00:42:43,616
but she passed away
many years ago.

526
00:42:45,729 --> 00:42:49,597
Lafferty, I know absolutely
nothing about you.

527
00:42:49,633 --> 00:42:51,692
Maybe that's just as well, ma'am.

528
00:42:51,735 --> 00:42:53,566
Do you think you should
be getting some rest?

529
00:42:53,604 --> 00:42:55,697
- You have a long trip ahead of you.
- No, I'll be fine.

530
00:42:55,739 --> 00:42:57,832
I can take care of this
while you're away.

531
00:42:57,875 --> 00:43:00,002
No.

532
00:43:01,946 --> 00:43:05,211
I had a-- a child
with my first marriage.

533
00:43:05,249 --> 00:43:07,740
She only lived for 24 hours.

534
00:43:08,886 --> 00:43:11,013
What do you think
the point of that is?

535
00:43:11,055 --> 00:43:13,023
I'm terribly sorry
to hear that.

536
00:43:13,057 --> 00:43:15,218
I mean, supposedly
everything happens for a reason.

537
00:43:15,259 --> 00:43:18,956
You know, part of the Book of Life
or the Great Mandala.

538
00:43:18,996 --> 00:43:20,361
You know?

539
00:43:20,397 --> 00:43:22,365
What do you think
about that?

540
00:43:22,399 --> 00:43:24,060
I...

541
00:43:24,101 --> 00:43:27,070
I-- it's whatever
gets you through the night.

542
00:43:27,104 --> 00:43:29,572
I mean, I'd hardly
be the one to judge it.

543
00:43:29,607 --> 00:43:34,408
So the snail and the orchids
and you and l?

544
00:43:34,445 --> 00:43:38,108
You smell divine, by the way.
Is that Norell?

545
00:43:38,148 --> 00:43:40,309
- It is.
- I gave you that, didn't l?

546
00:43:40,351 --> 00:43:42,148
You did. You gave it to me
and I wear it every day.

547
00:43:42,186 --> 00:43:43,881
I wouldn't be caught
dead without it.

548
00:43:43,921 --> 00:43:46,355
Well, that's part of
the plan, you see?

549
00:43:46,390 --> 00:43:48,017
What about the apple?

550
00:43:48,058 --> 00:43:50,458
- Do you think this apple here has...
- Yeah.

551
00:43:50,494 --> 00:43:52,189
...a part in the great--
the great plan?

552
00:43:52,229 --> 00:43:54,663
Yeah. I mean,
events may seem random,

553
00:43:54,698 --> 00:43:56,928
but there is a plan.

554
00:43:56,967 --> 00:43:59,959
Unfortunately, it just may
not unfold quickly enough

555
00:44:00,004 --> 00:44:03,269
for us to really understand why
it's happening. You know what I mean?

556
00:44:03,307 --> 00:44:04,934
Sure.

557
00:44:08,746 --> 00:44:11,214
I-- I knew this lrish lad

558
00:44:11,248 --> 00:44:12,738
in Philadelphia.

559
00:44:12,783 --> 00:44:14,751
His name was Freezer.
That's how cool he was.

560
00:44:14,785 --> 00:44:16,480
And he had everything
going for him--

561
00:44:16,520 --> 00:44:19,080
he was handsome,
he was fun, he was warm-hearted.

562
00:44:19,123 --> 00:44:23,025
We were up for the same
job at this chichi hotel,

563
00:44:23,060 --> 00:44:24,618
the Bellevue in Stratford.

564
00:44:24,662 --> 00:44:27,153
I knew he would get the job.
No one could resist

565
00:44:27,197 --> 00:44:29,392
Freezer when he
turned on the charm.

566
00:44:29,433 --> 00:44:32,095
Anyways, on the day
of the interviews

567
00:44:32,136 --> 00:44:34,798
he steps off the curb
and he breaks his foot.

568
00:44:34,838 --> 00:44:36,863
And I get the job.

569
00:44:36,907 --> 00:44:38,841
And that's how I get to
meet Miss Taylor.

570
00:44:38,876 --> 00:44:40,400
She introduces me
to Miss Lee.

571
00:44:40,444 --> 00:44:42,810
- Then it's...
- lntroduces you...

572
00:44:42,846 --> 00:44:44,780
-...to you.
-...to me.

573
00:44:44,815 --> 00:44:46,544
'Cause you read it
on the resume.

574
00:44:46,583 --> 00:44:48,949
Oh, so that's--
that was your path.

575
00:44:48,986 --> 00:44:51,011
That was your journey, exactly.

576
00:44:51,055 --> 00:44:53,353
- The Mandala, exactly.
- Mandala.

577
00:44:53,390 --> 00:44:56,154
Oh Jesus, smell this.

578
00:44:57,695 --> 00:45:00,459
Mm. Incredible, huh?

579
00:45:00,497 --> 00:45:04,263
Very few of these guys actually
even have a scent. Isn't that tragic?

580
00:45:04,301 --> 00:45:05,996
- Yeah, they're beautiful.
- So sad.

581
00:45:06,036 --> 00:45:08,129
Miss Duke, do you think
I should be packing

582
00:45:08,172 --> 00:45:11,073
the Persian outfits
that you mentioned

583
00:45:11,108 --> 00:45:12,769
for your trip?

584
00:45:12,810 --> 00:45:14,368
I don't know.
What do you think?

585
00:45:14,411 --> 00:45:17,471
I don't know. I've never performed
in a belly-dancing troupe.

586
00:45:17,514 --> 00:45:22,042
It's not belly dancing,
it's dance oriental.

587
00:45:22,086 --> 00:45:23,576
Oh, that's Chinese, is it?

588
00:45:23,620 --> 00:45:27,681
No, look, it's the Earth
and then the core

589
00:45:27,725 --> 00:45:29,716
and then out.

590
00:45:29,760 --> 00:45:32,820
See? It's as if your entire being

591
00:45:32,863 --> 00:45:35,661
is concentrated,
every ounce of it right here.

592
00:45:35,699 --> 00:45:37,030
- Right.
- You see?

593
00:45:37,067 --> 00:45:38,864
- Sure.
- Right there, you understand?

594
00:45:38,902 --> 00:45:41,871
It's like...

595
00:45:41,905 --> 00:45:43,338
Like that.

596
00:45:43,373 --> 00:45:46,103
- Yeah.
- Feel that?

597
00:45:46,143 --> 00:45:47,974
- Go ahead, try it. Try it.
- No.

598
00:45:48,011 --> 00:45:50,002
I think it's more of--
more of a girl thing.

599
00:45:50,047 --> 00:45:53,039
No no, it's the most fun you could ever
have without actually touching yourself.

600
00:45:53,083 --> 00:45:54,311
- Go ahead.
- No, I couldn't.

601
00:45:54,351 --> 00:45:56,046
- Come on.
- No.

602
00:45:56,086 --> 00:45:57,383
- See, like this?
- Yeah.

603
00:45:57,421 --> 00:45:59,412
Some men actually find it
very seductive.

604
00:45:59,456 --> 00:46:00,684
I'm sure they do.

605
00:46:00,724 --> 00:46:04,182
I mean, l-- I swing
in the other direction,

606
00:46:04,228 --> 00:46:06,492
if you catch my drift.

607
00:46:07,698 --> 00:46:10,565
Cat--?
Yes, I catch it.

608
00:46:10,601 --> 00:46:12,296
I caught it.

609
00:46:12,336 --> 00:46:13,894
I have it.

610
00:46:13,937 --> 00:46:15,632
All right, well it's just that l--

611
00:46:15,672 --> 00:46:19,039
I think it--
it's mesmerizing.

612
00:46:19,076 --> 00:46:21,306
How did I look just now?
I mean, tell me the truth.

613
00:46:21,345 --> 00:46:23,210
I mean, did I look ridiculous?

614
00:46:23,247 --> 00:46:25,010
- What do you mean?
- I mean, was it clumsy?

615
00:46:25,048 --> 00:46:26,948
- Did I look clumsy? Did I look awful?
- No no.

616
00:46:26,984 --> 00:46:29,953
I'll tell you what,
you looked happy.

617
00:46:32,122 --> 00:46:34,215
Happy?

618
00:46:34,258 --> 00:46:36,692
Yeah, just...

619
00:46:50,707 --> 00:46:53,801
- Break a leg, Miss Duke.
- God forbid.

620
00:47:16,533 --> 00:47:19,559
Miss Duke would like two men
on duty at any given time.

621
00:47:19,603 --> 00:47:22,572
That's one inside the house
and one patrolling the grounds.

622
00:47:22,606 --> 00:47:24,665
Also four dogs.

623
00:47:24,708 --> 00:47:27,404
Nobody's to get in through
the front gate when she's away

624
00:47:27,444 --> 00:47:29,810
except the gardeners
and the pool guy.

625
00:47:29,847 --> 00:47:32,816
They have been issued
with passes like this.

626
00:47:32,850 --> 00:47:35,250
And if you set off
the sprinkler system

627
00:47:35,285 --> 00:47:38,345
with one of those,
you'll be destroying $30 million worth

628
00:47:38,388 --> 00:47:40,948
of art and antiques.

629
00:47:40,991 --> 00:47:43,084
Thanks, gentlemen.

630
00:48:19,429 --> 00:48:21,920
Oh, l-- I thought
you'd gone home.

631
00:48:21,965 --> 00:48:24,661
I've been having
a wee clear out of my room.

632
00:48:24,701 --> 00:48:26,566
You know what it's like.

633
00:48:26,603 --> 00:48:28,400
- I'll take that out for you.
- That's okay.

634
00:48:28,438 --> 00:48:31,168
- It's no big deal.
- It's fine, thanks anyway.

635
00:48:31,208 --> 00:48:32,971
Thanks.

636
00:48:34,745 --> 00:48:37,873
Lafferty, change of plans.
I leave for London tomorrow.

637
00:48:37,915 --> 00:48:40,008
Book the Connaught.
Make sure to tell Elton I'm coming.

638
00:48:40,050 --> 00:48:43,349
Send over my Russian fox
and the new white sable pronto.

639
00:48:43,387 --> 00:48:45,878
I rejoin the tour
in Washington on the 15th

640
00:48:45,923 --> 00:48:47,891
and I'm running
to Hawaii after that.

641
00:48:47,925 --> 00:48:50,052
So make sure
all the linens are changed.

642
00:48:50,093 --> 00:48:53,654
Tell the painters I want them
out of there by March 10th,

643
00:48:53,697 --> 00:48:56,165
or I'm invoking
the penalty clause.

644
00:48:56,199 --> 00:48:59,498
In no way am I kidding.
Sincerely, Doris Duke.

645
00:48:59,536 --> 00:49:02,198
Oh, PS-- have my new
jewelry appraised

646
00:49:02,239 --> 00:49:04,298
and listed in the policy.
Sotheby's can do it.

647
00:49:04,341 --> 00:49:07,037
I prefer that nice Kathy,
but if it has to be the other one,

648
00:49:07,077 --> 00:49:08,908
so be it.

649
00:49:14,685 --> 00:49:16,448
- Welcome back, Miss Duke.
- Oh, thank you.

650
00:49:16,486 --> 00:49:18,477
I am so glad to be back.

651
00:49:33,570 --> 00:49:35,162
Are you growing your hair?

652
00:49:35,205 --> 00:49:37,639
A bit, I am. Yeah.

653
00:49:37,674 --> 00:49:39,699
Come here.

654
00:49:41,111 --> 00:49:43,045
Here.

655
00:49:43,080 --> 00:49:45,105
- Look.
- What?

656
00:49:45,148 --> 00:49:46,809
Look.

657
00:49:46,850 --> 00:49:48,818
What do you think?

658
00:49:48,852 --> 00:49:50,752
I think it looks a bit puny.

659
00:49:50,787 --> 00:49:53,221
Well, you've got to give it time.

660
00:49:53,256 --> 00:49:54,689
- I like it.
- You do?

661
00:49:54,725 --> 00:49:56,317
Mm-hm.

662
00:49:56,360 --> 00:49:59,352
I hope that your tour
went well?

663
00:49:59,396 --> 00:50:02,854
Oh, the arts in America,
Lafferty, don't get me started.

664
00:50:02,899 --> 00:50:05,527
You know, sometimes there
were more of us onstage

665
00:50:05,569 --> 00:50:07,127
than there were in the audience.

666
00:50:07,170 --> 00:50:08,694
I'm sorry to hear that, ma'am.

667
00:50:08,739 --> 00:50:10,536
It wasn't a total disaster,

668
00:50:10,574 --> 00:50:12,599
- I made a little friend.
- Oh, you did?

669
00:50:12,642 --> 00:50:14,872
Mm-hm.
A kid in the company.

670
00:50:14,911 --> 00:50:17,106
Oh, amazing dancer.
I thought he was gay.

671
00:50:17,147 --> 00:50:20,241
And actually, so did he. But you know,
we have to leave ourselves open

672
00:50:20,283 --> 00:50:22,911
to all the possibilities.

673
00:50:22,953 --> 00:50:25,581
Indeed, it's true.

674
00:50:26,690 --> 00:50:29,784
You know, you should
really wear more color

675
00:50:29,826 --> 00:50:31,885
to kind of lift your face.

676
00:50:31,928 --> 00:50:33,520
- Look at this, for instance.
- Oh.

677
00:50:33,563 --> 00:50:35,292
Put this shirt--
now what does that shirt say?

678
00:50:35,332 --> 00:50:36,856
- That shirt says...
- Too much.

679
00:50:36,900 --> 00:50:38,390
-..."look at me."
- It certainly does.

680
00:50:38,435 --> 00:50:41,199
You know, your shirt
doesn't say anything at all.

681
00:50:41,238 --> 00:50:42,830
See what I mean?

682
00:50:42,873 --> 00:50:46,001
Actually, Miss Duke, there is
one thing of yours that I love.

683
00:50:46,043 --> 00:50:48,375
- It's that scarf there.
- Oh.

684
00:50:48,412 --> 00:50:50,937
- I think that's the most beautiful...
- Well, yeah, let's see.

685
00:50:50,981 --> 00:50:54,314
Uh-huh, that brings out
the blue in your baby blues.

686
00:50:54,351 --> 00:50:55,943
- It does?
- Mm-hm.

687
00:50:55,986 --> 00:50:57,749
What about my eyes?

688
00:50:57,788 --> 00:50:59,278
- What about them?
- The shadow.

689
00:50:59,322 --> 00:51:00,914
- You look great.
- Mm.

690
00:51:00,957 --> 00:51:02,948
May-- um, maybe it's
a bit strong.

691
00:51:02,993 --> 00:51:04,688
- Really?
- Just at the corner.

692
00:51:04,728 --> 00:51:06,525
- May l?
- Yes.

693
00:51:06,563 --> 00:51:09,054
Just smudge it out a bit.

694
00:51:09,099 --> 00:51:11,260
There, like that.

695
00:51:11,301 --> 00:51:13,235
- Mm.
- That looks great.

696
00:51:13,270 --> 00:51:15,966
Maybe you should
wear a little eye shadow.

697
00:51:16,006 --> 00:51:17,667
- No, I shouldn't.
- Just a touch.

698
00:51:17,707 --> 00:51:20,437
- I don't think I should.
- You could try it.

699
00:51:23,613 --> 00:51:25,137
What do you think of this?

700
00:51:25,182 --> 00:51:26,740
I think it's gorgeous.

701
00:51:26,783 --> 00:51:29,911
Okay, why don't you press it?

702
00:51:29,953 --> 00:51:32,820
Um, Miss Duke?

703
00:51:34,858 --> 00:51:37,656
I wondered if I could have next
Thursday evening off?

704
00:51:37,694 --> 00:51:39,924
Why?

705
00:51:39,963 --> 00:51:42,830
Just personal reasons.

706
00:51:42,866 --> 00:51:46,427
You know that Maltese cross
that I brought back from Paris?

707
00:51:46,470 --> 00:51:48,097
Yeah, it's in the safe.

708
00:51:48,138 --> 00:51:49,969
How do think that would go?

709
00:51:50,006 --> 00:51:52,634
With this?
It would, yeah, absolutely would.

710
00:51:52,676 --> 00:51:55,167
Well, when you say personal,
what do you mean?

711
00:51:55,212 --> 00:51:58,272
I mean, do you have to go to a funeral
or have a procedure or...?

712
00:51:58,315 --> 00:52:01,512
It's just,
I have a date, sort of.

713
00:52:01,551 --> 00:52:03,576
Really?

714
00:52:03,620 --> 00:52:05,645
Where did you meet?

715
00:52:05,689 --> 00:52:07,953
- I haven't met him yet.
- It's a blind date?

716
00:52:07,991 --> 00:52:09,754
Yeah, well, through the personals.

717
00:52:09,793 --> 00:52:12,921
- "lrish Echo."
- "Village Voice."

718
00:52:12,963 --> 00:52:16,421
How uncharacteristically
daring of you, Lafferty.

719
00:52:16,466 --> 00:52:18,593
Are you a stone or a sponge?

720
00:52:18,635 --> 00:52:20,364
- Oh, never mind.
- What, excuse me?

721
00:52:20,403 --> 00:52:22,132
Well no, don't answer.
Never mind.

722
00:52:22,172 --> 00:52:24,037
Permission granted.

723
00:52:24,074 --> 00:52:26,167
Miss Duke, thanks very much.
I appreciate it.

724
00:52:26,209 --> 00:52:28,473
I'll have this pressed at once.

725
00:52:29,579 --> 00:52:32,343
Oh oh oh oh oh... scarf.

726
00:52:32,382 --> 00:52:34,850
Oh, excuse me.

727
00:53:47,991 --> 00:53:50,551
- Bravo.
- I so love that one.

728
00:53:50,594 --> 00:53:52,528
- Oh my God.
- You sounded great, Miss Duke.

729
00:53:52,562 --> 00:53:54,359
Peggy Lee couldn't
do it better herself.

730
00:53:54,397 --> 00:53:56,524
She could and she did
and you know it.

731
00:53:56,566 --> 00:53:58,557
'Cause Bernard used to
work for Miss Lee.

732
00:53:58,602 --> 00:54:00,695
- Is that right?
- No, I just made the phone calls,

733
00:54:00,737 --> 00:54:02,568
and I booked her rooms,
and I held the umbrellas,

734
00:54:02,606 --> 00:54:04,403
and I opened the doors,
that sort of thing, you know.

735
00:54:04,441 --> 00:54:05,999
- Want some more champagne?
- Please.

736
00:54:06,042 --> 00:54:07,407
Thank you.

737
00:54:07,444 --> 00:54:09,435
Now I heard that song
for the first time

738
00:54:09,479 --> 00:54:11,208
in Las Vegas
at Caesar's Palace.

739
00:54:11,248 --> 00:54:13,045
That's a real
crowd-pleaser, that song.

740
00:54:13,083 --> 00:54:14,710
Mm, mm.

741
00:54:14,751 --> 00:54:17,447
What was the one that
she did about the masochist?

742
00:54:17,487 --> 00:54:19,250
- I don't know, what song is that?
- You know.

743
00:54:19,289 --> 00:54:22,190
Where the guy is treating her horribly
and she's just loving it.

744
00:54:22,225 --> 00:54:23,817
That sounds like
the story of my life.

745
00:54:23,860 --> 00:54:25,350
- No, it's my life.
- No, it's my life.

746
00:54:25,395 --> 00:54:27,124
- It is not your life.
- No, it is my life.

747
00:54:27,163 --> 00:54:28,562
I think it's all of our lives.

748
00:54:30,166 --> 00:54:31,565
Well, go ahead, sing it.

749
00:54:31,601 --> 00:54:33,228
- Now?
- Now.

750
00:54:33,270 --> 00:54:35,295
We only have now.

751
00:54:36,940 --> 00:54:38,703
Uh, wait a minute...

752
00:54:47,284 --> 00:54:48,911
That's it.

753
00:54:51,988 --> 00:54:55,424
You have to imagine a wee black dress
